deck_excerpt: Master Duel, Rose Dragon, Plant, OTK
deck_description:
It's Rose Dragon! Yeah as cool as Rose Dragons are in the Anime they are quite difficult to pilot, so let me explain more in Detail.

If you decide to play Rose Dragon it's like playing 2 Decks at once, so be prepared and practice:

 

The Rose Dragons

The Dream Combo is opening Red and White Rose Dragon. Summon Black Rose Dragon ---> Search Frozen Rose ---> Mill Revival Rose ----> Special Roxrose Dragon ---> Search whatever fits the Situation ---> Summon Ruddy Rose Dragon.

But beware that that's not that strong going first. Going first a Crossrose Dragon +Black Garden or a plant on your field is way better to interrupt plays with a sudden Black Rose Dragon summon during his turn. Again beware to not do it mid chain since BRD (Black Rose Dragon) will miss his timing then. 

Roxrose Dragon, Blue Rose Dragon & Blooming of the Darkest Rose all help to prevent the loss of a Black Rose Dragon when he destroys all Cards. White Rose Dragon, Garden Rose Maiden and Black Garden are able to revive lost Rose Dragons.

Combining Black Rose Moonlight Dragon with Black Garden allows a Monster Bounce which can't be negated since you can Chainblock the effect with Black Garden itself.

As for Ruddy Rose Dragon, beware using his banishing effect early since you too will loose a lot of Graveyard effects and possible plants for banishing for other effects. Think of it as a big blowout midgame to finish the game easily then. 

There's a lot more to think about here but that are things you will experience for yourself if you play with this Deck more often. 

 

The Plants

The 2nd essencial focus in this Deck are the plants. Ruddy Rose Witch enables a search for the Witch of the Black Rose and puts a Rose Fairy on top of the Deck which results in another easy way to access Black Rose Dragon and especially Roxrose Dragon but only with no other cards on your side of the field. 

Lonefire Blossom helps to fill the Graveyard with plants for Mark of the Rose, a powerful Snatch Steal like Spell and she can easily summon Tytannial or Gigaplant.

Tytannial has to be the best going first move possible since she +Black Garden equals almost infinite targeting negates for anywhere on the field. It's very easy to destroy whole Combo setups with her and win the game from there, a real powerhouse to play. 

The Rose Tentacles are another powerplayer with Black Garden together. If you equip her with Thorn of Malice it's very easy to OTK the opponent with very little setup. 

Lastly Queen of Thorns makes up for a nice floodgate which is another good going first setup. There's a lot more to think about and many Combos which I can't go into detail here. 

 

Final thoughts

This Deck can easily destroy all cards on the field every turn and prevent Combo decks from playing the game with Tytannial. Black Garden cripples many Decks and creates many special gamestates from which you can easily overrun your opponent.

But sometimes the synergy between the own cards doesn't work out the way you want and bigger towers can be difficult to clear. It's a difficult deck to play optimal. 

If you like Rose Dragons be sure to give this Deck a try. I find it easy to go into Platin League in Master Duel with it. Beyond that it's getting difficult to progress against certain matchups.

Overall Rating: ★★★☆☆☆

My Despia Bystial Branded deck - the flex/side spots in the main are the 3x Kashtira Fenrir, 3x Forbidden Droplet, and 3x Infinite Impermanence.

The idea is that these 9 cards are hopefully generic 'good' cards, which can play well enough going 1st or 2nd into Ishizu Tear, Floo, and Rogue decks.

Sideboard is 3x Dimension Shifter and 3x Dimensional Fissure for Ishizu Tear, subbing out 3x Fenrir, 1x Mercourier, 1x Branded in Red, and maybe 1x Albion?  Thinking that these 6 'Dimension' cards pair well w/ our Bystial handtraps, and that Branded in Red is hard to play against the Ishizu Tear GY shufflers (and is a nonbo w/ our shifter/fissure), Mercourier runs into the same problem (must be sent to the GY to activate), and that Albion is an Upstart Goblin that depends on the GY being available, so it is turned off by shifter/fissure.

Against Floo, I'm thinking of subbing in the Zombie World, Necroworld Banshee, and Feather Duster.  We would sub out 2x Druiswurm and 1x Saronir.  These Bystials should be harder to get value on due to Floo not being Light/Dark, and Zombie World should lock them out, while Feather Duster is just generically good.

The remaining cards - 3x Evenly Matched and 3x Cosmic Cyclone, should be generically good going second or into decks that depend on spells/traps.
The concept of the deck is to mix flodgates with boardbreakers to create an anti-meta deck that can go both first and second.

Deck I run on master duel to some success

Built around a standard Trickstar engine (single corobane for defensive purposes). Standard Windwitch engine to Synchro out Crystal Wing (who can't be destroyed by the opponent's card effects thanks to Snow Bell), OR Diamond Bell, who can destroy cards super easily with Trickstar's needle damage. As a general rule I would SS Crystal Wing if you're going first, and Diamond Bell if you're going second (otherwise Diamond Bell won't have much to destroy). The Droll/Reincarnation combo isn't as meta anymore, and thus can come as a nasty surprise for your opponent if you can pull it off. Obviously we also need interaction to protect our pieces, so I've completed the deck with what I found interesting (and also budget).

*The Two copies of Metaverse enables the deck to have an incredibly consistent Trickstar Engine despite Terraforming being Limited. Trap Trick, Metaverse, and Terraforming all represent Light Stage (which in turn represents Candina, etc.).

I've figured out the playstyle of my builds, they're mainly supposed to control the game with einsatz and shield to eventually link climb into their strongest links.

deck_excerpt: Wyrms are still fun and effective!
deck_description:
This deck is a classic from early to mid 2022! While it has fell off due to Tearlament and Spright dominance, I still think it has a place today!

Ruddy Rose Dragon is a highly effective card this deck can use, due to it banishing everything from both players grave, it forces the Ishizu Tear player to use their Mudora and Keldo effects. Other options to run could be Dimensional barrier to stop all fusion summons for the turn and also a different form of Grave hate, like Necrovalley or Soul Drain. I personally don't like either option as it screws with Swordsoul lines with Vessel for the Dragon Cycle and Swordsoul Sacred Summit.

This deck has a really strong going second build too, using Triple Tactics Talent, Lightning Storm, etc

deck_excerpt: A different take on the fight against tear Zero
deck_description:
Good day to all who are interested on my spicy take.

Firsty this is based on my experience play at my local, and my understanding of playing this archtype and that of Tears

At first glance, my deck list makes no sence, compared to others i have found online and on youtube, mostly because i truly believe this a control deck at heart, like eldrich, altergeist and labyrinth. However the tools at this deck disposible needs you to have a very good understand other archtype well, this in a anti-meta deck afterall.

This deck does not like flunder, which is why there is backrow hate build in, and generic hand traps like imperm and ash. Against tears and graveyard reliant deck, is where this deck excels. Like tear with havnis, you play on your opponent turn, banishing resources left, right and centre.

The design of this version is to hopefully not combo to the point of being nib and have nothing to clap back with, however the OTK lines are all there, once you have simplify the board state. 

Digging for Martha and Pax, these two cards are your playmaker and the bloodline of the deck, however this is not entirely true because of how it is designed, (i basically got tired of being nib and have nothing to come back with). vadis and arment is full combo on your opponents turn, carpiderm works overtime, when you know what you opponent is playing. vadis into any exosister, arment into gabine or mikalis, gives you a banish or negate, call out their play starter with carpiderm, and watch them make a imperfect board.

flunder is robina, @gnister is the field card, tears is kit, branded is lubellion/ branded fusion.

The deck does not rely on the die roll, they will expect you to make a full board but keeping the board simple and cut of there lines from OTKs gives you plenty of follow up. the side deck alters the profile to a more familiar combo deck found in everyone else's profile.

the deck still natural run shifter even in this control form.

The biggest twist in this deck profile is the addition of lord of the heavenly prison, to active protect backrow, instead of judgement it can also grab any spell or trap for follow out play when summoned. The addition of megaclop in the extra deck is because there were a lot of situation where i had enough xyz to make and, I had a really hard time outing scareclaw tri-heart. the monster is a tank, and against tear they need exactly the field card to out it, but the ability to take your opponent card for a xyz in the grave, gives a bit of grind game, it is the only graveyard interaction and the effect triggers martha to xyz. win-win

i have really enjoyed this deck this month, managing to come second in my local, the new banlist start soon, and never being a fan of floorgates, i hope this take is insightful, and i may come back to it, if it gets new support, or if tears runs too rampert with the unlimited reprints coming out.

SCRAP DECEMBER 2022

The main goal of this deck is banish the field with quick Synchros during your opponent's turn. Mainly summoning Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti  and having Shif, Fairy of the Ghoti  and Paces, Light of the Ghoti  Banished at the end of your turn, since that gives you access to Ghoti of the Deep Beyond . The Adventure package is there to bait or negate Hand Traps and other forms of disruption, and the token can be use for synchro summoning as well. It works since you rarely use any normal summon effect, only Paces into Eanoc, Sentry of the Ghoti  if you don´t open the Adventure stuff or Beautunaful Princess  if you draw it and not One for One.

Neo Space HERO deck for Domain Format, a casual multiplayer free-for-all format inspired by MTG Commander format.

Neo Space Connector can special summon Elemental HERO Neos or any Neo-Spacian. Using him as the Deckmaster gives me access to LIGHT, Warrior, Neo Space or Neo-Spacian monsters.

Use your Deckmaster to setup future plays:

  • Neo Space Connector tutor for Elemental HERO Neos / Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and then search for:
    • Elemental HERO Stratos for a HERO search.
    • Neo Space Pathfinder for a contact fusion play.
    • Elemental HERO Blazeman for a fusion play.
    • Cross Keeper or Elemental HERO Liquid Soldier for a recovery play.

Cards for further testing:

  • None at this moment.

P.D. I didn't include Elemental HERO Air Neos for budget reasons.

deck_excerpt: What if we used all the floodgates?
deck_description:
The Weather Painters are an archetype of Fairy monsters which each represent a different weather phenomenom. Each of the maindeck monsters has a unique effect to it specifically and additionally all Weather monsters can banish themselves until the next standby phase to activate the effects of the archetype's Spell and Traps. Seeing many of these monsters place spell and traps and banish themselves as cost for effects the deck can run almost every floodgate under the sun. The deck is only mildly inconvenienced by powerful floodgates Anti-Spell Fragrance, Skill Drain & Macro Cosmos, and Rivelry of the Warlord & Dimentional Fissure play into the deck's strenghts.

With the release of DIFO the deck got its almost custom card Field Spell which lets you:

1. Place 1 Weather S/T when used

2. Perform an additional normal summon of a Weather monster

3. Use The Weather spell and traps as link materials

The field spell has enabled the deck to make its Link-3 monster The Weather Painter Rainbow on turn 1 which turns every Weather monster it points at into an omni-negate. EVERY. SINGLE. TURN. 

With the december banlist The Weather got a decent boost in power. More floodgates then ever are now availible to the deck which increases its potential in the current meta significantly. Macro Cosmos and Dimentional Fissure to 3 is massive for the deck because it doesn't care for banishing, and while Macro Cosmos is less desirable seeing we do sometimes want our spells/traps to go to the GY it is not a hard requirement.

 

The Weather Painters

3x Snow - This is your main starter. Snow can place a Weather spell/trap which helps you search for Snowy Canvas.

3x Cloud - Spell/Trap recursion while on the field, works amazingly with the Field Spell

2x Thundery - Can place any Weather Spell/Trap on the field at the cost of a continous Spell/Trap. This helps you out your own floodgates if you want to get rid of them for whatever reason

1x Sun - Can summon itself from the GY at the cost of a continous S/T

1x Rain - if special summoned (which its unbanish effect counts as) you can place 1 Weather S/T from your hand. This helps you bypass your own Anti-Spell Fragrance

1x Aurora - Protects your Weather S/T. Easily brought out using Rainbowed Canvas

Weather S/T

3x Snowy Canvas - Banish a Weather Monster to search any Weather Card. Used to search for the Field Spell

3x The Weather Forecast - See above for the effects. This card is just broken

1x Rainy Canvas - We just need additional Canvas numbers and this is the least bad spell availible. Returns a spell/trap to the hand, can be used to out difficult cards like TCOBO

2x Thundery Canvas - Can bounch an oppenent's monster during the damage step. Great card against any Extra Deck monster

1x Rainbowed Canvas -   Can Special Summon 1 Weather Monster. Helps bring out Aurora and turn after turn this adds bodies onto the field/

Other cards

1x Pankertops - We often find ourselves with an empty board which can make bringing out Pank easy

3x Piri Reis Map - Snow is a 0 atk and your main starter. Of course we run Piri

3x Imperm - Best handtrap in the game

Floodgates

3x Macro Cosmos & Dimentional Dissue - Banishing monsters is fun especially when your opponent is running a graveyard deck

2x Anti-Spell - We place spells so we dont care about Anti-Spell

2x Skill Drain - Banish for cost means we can play under Skill Drain. We do lose things like the on field effect of Cloud but it is a worthwhile trade-off

2x Summon Limit - Moonbow can banish 2 of your opponent's monsters on a quick effect which will be summoned next turn. This can effectivly lock your opponent from summoning

Extra Deck

2x Rainbow - See above for the effects. this card is just broken that we can bring it out first turn

2x Moonbow - Can lock your opponent from summoning in combination with Summon Limit. Also if it gets destroys it just summons a Rainbow

2x Break Sword - Our main monsters are level 3s so we run rank 3

1x Leviar - We banish so Leviar definitly has its usage returning to the hand especially seeing we can normal summon twice

1x Zeus - We run XYZ monsters so we run Zeus it is that simple

The rest are just the usual list of suspects of Link Monsters, we dont often go into them but all of them can be useful. Also if need be we can make a 5300 Accesscode

Side deck

3x Rivalry - We mainly play Fairy monsters so if the opponent is on some deck that runs multiple types we can lock them down

The rest is just your normal Side Deck cards with backrow hate, Lava Golem, DD Crow for GY decks going second, and Nibiru.

deck_name: Danger! with a side of Kaiju and a sprinkle of Lava Golem
deck_description: This deck allows you to mess up your friend's statagies as much as you want. Have fun.

Dark World deck with the new structure deck - thought i'd make this as I've seen a lot of deckbuilding mistakes in other dark world decks recently. Below I've explained the choices in tech cards/side deck cards and the choices that differ from most other dark world decks i've seen

-Reign-Beaux at 1 - it does nothing on the field, but is a useful extender so I would either have 1 or 2 copies, three isn't necessary
-Grapha at 2 - Due to searchability through Snoww and Reign-Beaux in addition to the decks fantastic draw power, 2 copies is all that is necessary
-Sillva at 1 - Searchable as above, plus, in combination with Ceruli and Akashic Magician, there is a recurrable anti-Fenrir loop where Ceruli being on your opponents side of the field will prevent Fenrir summons
-Gates at 2 - it's the most searchable card in the deck - it is also very rare that duels last long enough for 3 copies to be needed. The third copy never came up in testing
-Allure of Darkness over Dark World Dealings - DWD lets your opponent discard. Against Tears this is a big no-go. Side in DWD only after you know what your opponent is playing

-Mothman in side deck - Mothman is in the side deck because of the same reason DWD is in the side deck, only side in if you know your opponent is not playing Tearlaments
-Bigfoot and Nessie at 3 - As for Bigfoot, this is because the deck will contain more level 8s will synergise with Grapha for more drawpower from trade-in as well as provide more material for Hope-Harbinger, which will also combo with Ceruli for Fenrir-hate. Additionally, Bigfoot is good removal for D Fissure and Macro Cosmos now that they are unlimited as these anti-tear cards will be common in the current meta but are also very strong against DW. Nessie is at 3 over Thunderbird or Chupacabra (common picks in other DW decks) because it provides an additional search to get to Bigfoot, which is good for reasons already described. 

-Mask Change and dark law package - Mask Change II synergises well with the play style - additionally, banish from hand is broken against almost anything that isn't Floo

-Zalamander Catalyzer in side - free special summon of itself or a DW monster and becomes a 1 card resource loop

Other good tech choices: Gozen Match, Infip, Zephyros, Skill Drain, Dark World Punishment, Thunderbird, Chupacabra, Beginning of The End, Dark Ruler no More

Feel free to give feedback!

Overall there are things that can be changed in the decklist like the gishki beast, upstart, moray of averice, and the extra deck can be changed with whatever you want the only thingss that matter in the extra deck is elf, anemone, and abyss keeper.

This deck tries to draw through the entire deck, using spell cards, to get all 5 pieces of Exodia in your hand in one turn. Two turns if your opponent has a hand trap, but doesn't kill you on their next turn. Because I expect the opponent to have some way of stopping you from the FTK, I don't include cards like Into the Void and Card of Demise, so you can keep any pieces of Exodia in your hand, as this deck has no way of retrieving them from the graveyard.

Try to land a Royal Magical Library as soon as possible, to get the most out of its ability. Summoner Monk can tutor for it. Discarding a Cursed Bamboo Sword is the best.

Can also use Foolish Burial Goods and Dark World Dealings to send Cursed Bamboo Sword to the graveyard to activate its ability.

Try to use Toon Table of Contents to tutor for the other copies of Toon Table of Contents and then finally Red-Eyes Toon Dragon as soon as possible, to thin your deck. Drawing those cards otherwise will end up clogging your hand.

Allure of Darkness works well with the extra copies of Summoner Monk and Red-Eyes Toon Dragon.

Try to hold the symmetrical draw effects (One Day of Peace, Card of Fate, Contract with Don Thousand) as long as possible, so you don't give the opponent a chance to draw a hand trap.

Giant Ballpark  is perhaps the only playable card from the archetype that is meant to be used to make a Weevil Underwood themed deck, it is actually good enough to make it the center of this deck alongside 2 very good generic engines that actually have synergy with Giant Ballpark: Tenyi and Adventurer. First, let's talk about the insect side of the deck: we play 4 copies of Giant Ballpark (3 copies of itself and the one copy of Terraforming), a fantastic card, if you don't know what it does all I can say is read the card cause it does A LOT. We then play 2 copies of Gokipole, when sent to the graveyard it searches/special summons a level 4 normal insect monster and then destroys a monster with 1200+ ATK (Since our main target is Killer Needle, which is 1200 ATK); our main ways to get Gokipole to the grave are Foolish Burial, Fateful Adventure, Forbidden Droplet, Inzektor Picofalena and of course Giant Ballpark. Moving on to the engines, not much needs to be said about Adventurer Cards other than the fact that Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon has less chances of being a brick because of all of the non-effect monsters that we play. The Tenyi engine also has their own card with a bounce effect in Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda, and their turn 1 play is making Draco Berserker of the Tenyi using any non-effect monster + Vessel for the Dragon Cycle, which sends Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna to grave and adds Tenyi Spirit - Adhara to hand, we summon Adhara and use Ashuna's effect (Which locks you into wyrms only! Remember that) to summon a Vishuda from deck in order to sync Adhara and Vishuda off for Draco Berserker, not as strong as Wandering Gryphon Rider as a turn 1 play but still pretty good; lastly, there is Tenyi Spirit - Shthana, which acts as a handtrap and as an extender for both link and XYZ plays.

deck_name: Invoked - Ishizu - Branded - Bystial - Tearlaments post YCS Costa Rica (TCG)
deck_excerpt: An assortment of fusion goodies for the average fusion deck enjoyer (HEROs not included)
deck_description:
So here is the deal: I may now be going somewhere in life, but unfortunately Tearlaments is not. It still sits as the premiere deck to play despite banning of "Curious, The Lightsworn Dominion" and soon to be hits of the Ishizu and Bystial engine (Bystial isn't entirely their doing, but we know that Tearlaments will be scapegoated for the Bystial hits in order to not give Kashtira anymore needed fuel coming their Spring 2023). Now what is anything but new is that not only Branded, but Invoked wreaks the neverending body count that Tearlaments have been putting up with since their release. I will explain more below; but keep in mind out of two I added to the Tearlaments arsenal, I do like Branded for the consistency (despite how easy still is to get Mechaba and possibly Purgatrio on the field if I ever wanted to play it). For now all remains the same with the same song and dance we've been dealing with since the beginning.

 

   The Invoked engine in the variant I made is the standard "go for Mechaba and flank opposing staples" kind of scenario. Granted I regretted to add Purgatrio because of "Spright Elf", but then I came to realize how playing "Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly tired Tapir" is more important than worrying about "Ash blossom & Joyous Spring" this format. However the result for this is about a forty percent success rate of summoning Mechaba (or even Augoeides), for the reason being that Aleister (and partially Invocation) is sacrificed for the milling effects of the Ishizu and Tearlament cards. When on the field though (Mechaba) is pretty damn useful to have alongside your other comrades.

 

   The Branded engine has been on the rise as of late due to consistency and how it play wells with Tearlaments in general (at least in my opinion, but I'm not as smart compared to the enlightened intellectuals Yu-Gi-Oh has to offer nowadays). The most crucial benefactor of the Branded/Tearlaments synergy I've noticed is that you can go into Lubellion or Masquerade by simply using "Branded Fusion" to mill any Tearlaments monster with "Fallen of Albaz", which would do the normal Tearlaments effects as it would. With this also, you could go into "Predaplant Dragostapelia" with this scenario, but only to be careful as chain linking precisely is important. Bystial monsters can also be used in the Branded scheme as a last resort for Lubellion's effect to put "Bystial Druiswurm" and/or "Bystial Saronir" back in the deck for later use, but you shouldn't have to unless otherwise.

deck_excerpt: Been experimenting with an Exodia FTK and landed on this, for now, interested to see if I can make any improvements.
deck_description:
Been experimenting with Exodia FTK ideas for fun. I know this can improve, but it can be an FTK in most cases as long as you get a Piri or Library in your opening hand with 3 usable spells. Trash 2 of the pieces of Exodia with Magical Stone (for a Golden Bamboo Sword) and get them back with Mass Production. Your 2nd Magical Stone (again ideally bringing back a Golden Bamboo Sword) can trash unusable cards and/or a Cursed Bamboo. Use Foolish Burial for a Cursed Bamboo Sword. As long as you follow those rules, you'll probably win in about 3 out of every 5 games that you start first, in my experience. I've even gone on runs of as much as 10 wins in a row with this deck.

In Master Duel, an ideal win will usually end with 6,000+ xp, MUCH higher than typical (just don't expect to rise through the ranks with this deck all that much).
I found a really bad deck I made when I first started playing(i had no idea what I was doing). Soon I will make an updated ice barrier deck with whatever I can find in my collection of cards

deck_excerpt: Win in one turn with Exodia
deck_description:
This is my improved build. I made some deck changes to play less garnets. Allure of darkness is really powerful in this deck. You have to use three copies by banishing exodia pieces or summoner monk. Then you can use pot of acquisitiveness to shuffle your banished monsters back into the deck and draw one. Magicians souls can pop the cursed bamboo swords to draw one or two cards then you can use the effect of cursed bamboo sword to search golden or original bamboo sword. You can generate a massive amount of spellcounters by the bamboo engine and also the toon engine. Spell power grasp is also really good to generate even more spell counters. Here the card by card:

 

5x Pieces of Exodia: this is your primary and only win condition

3x Royal Magical Library: you always wanna see this card. Wouldn't cut

1x Summoner Monk: gets you access into library. Can discard cursed bamboo sword to generate advantage and also can be banished by allure of darkness

1x Anchamoufrite: no extra deck, this card acts like upstart

1x Magicians Souls: can destroy up to two cards and draw the same amount. Really good card, can destroy cursed bamboo sword and toon-world. You wanna destroy two copies of cursed bamboo sword

1x Illusion of Chaos: gets you access into souls and also makes souls life

3x Cursed Bamboo Sword: gets you access to golden bamboo sword and original bamboo sword. This card can bounce back one other cursed or original bamboo sword to hand to generate spellcounters but this is once per turn.

3x Golden Bamboo Sword: basically pot of greed

1x Original Bamboo Sword: makes golden bamboo sword life as well as cursed bamboo sword. You can send this card to your graveyard to equip one cursed bamboo sword from deck, but this doesn't generate a spellcounter. Nevertheless you have to do this so you don't draw into cursed bamboo sword

1x Foolish Burial Goods: to get cursed bamboo sword in the graveyard and search. This card is once per turn, so only one copy of it

3x Toon Table of Contents: this card can search itself and generates 4 spellcounters

1x Toon-World: Just fodder, one copy is fine

3x Magical Mallet: to shuffle back cards you don't need at the moment or to shuffle back exodia pieces

3x Allure of Darkness: basically pot of greed if you banish exodia pieces or summoner monk

1x Pot of Acquisitivness: allows you to shuffle 3 banished exodia pieces in the deck and draw one

1x Double Summon: sometimes you need a second library

1x Piri-Reis Map: you have to activate it at the start of main phase 1, gets you into library. In my former build I played 3 copies. This wasn't good enough because you don't wanna draw into the map. It's like if you have it, you activate it. But If you can't it's useless. I think 5 chances to get librarys is enough

1x Wonder Wand: this card is alwyas for magicians souls. Sometimes you have like 4 exodia pieces and only wonder wand and library on the field, then you can risk it

1x Top Share: this card can get you access into everything

2x Spell Power Grasp: searches itself and generates 2 spellcounters

1x Into the Void

1x Upstart Goblin

1x One Day of Peace

 

 

If you have recommendations or criticism please let me know. Thank you for your attention and time.

This is a fun FTK deck based around Cyberse Clock Dragon's (CD) ability to mill cards for attack. The inspiration for this deck comes from another post on ygoprodeck by user qbrsb3; I just made some changes to make the deck more consitent and more affordable for a Master Duel player.

The deck functions through Code Talker's incredible ability to extra deck spam. Cynet Codec is pivotal. It is the binding agent that without, the deck falls apart. If you don't start off with Codec, you can search for it by linking off Micro Coder. If you don't have Micro in hand, you can search it out using either Lady Debug or Cynet Mining. If you start of with Mining, and only Mining, I recommend searching out Lady Debug to search Micro just to thin out deck.

From there, link away; your goal is to gather up key ingredients while putting as many link monsters in the graveyard as possible. The cards needed are Cynet Fusion and Clock Wyvern, and to get them is simple, but can be a detriment if you don't have extenders. Clock Spartoi adds fusion, and Excode Talker can add Wyvern using Cynet Codec's effect. You will then fusion summon CD, activate its ability to mill those few extra cards, and immediately link it off to the graveyard. The final goal is to have a board that ends on any two cyberse monsters (including tokens) to link summon Clock Lizard.

Clock Lizard will send CD from your GY back to the extra deck and then fusion it back to field using material from the GY.

After milling your deck, Starliege can activate its ability to add Levianeer from GY to hand, Levianeer can special summon itself using only light monsters to summon Catapult Turtle, and finally Turtle can tribute a monster to inflict damage to your opponent equal to half the attack of the monster tributed. Tribute your 20k+ attack Clock Dragon for game.

Important things to consider before summoning Clock Dragon for the second time:

Pay attention to the link ratings you are using. CD mills an amount equal to the link rating used for its summon, so if you use more than the amount needed to mill the deck, the ability will not activate and you will fail the FTK. Likewise, if you don't use enough link ratings you might not mill your whole deck, and the final components to the FTK may not be available for use... and you'll fail the FTK.

Do not use Transcode Talker's ability! You will lock into Cyberse and you will fail the FTK.

Again, only use light monsters to summon Levianeer so you can use his ability to summon Turtle.

Codec is very powerful, consider your options when picking a cyberse to add for the maximum extension, and remember every monster's ability is a hard once per turn.

Finally, this is an FTK and RNG is not your friend. Not only do you need to win the coin flip and not brick on your opening, but this deck can not handle Ash Blossom. Nine times out of ten, if your opponent Ashes anything you will fail the FTK (Droll and Lockbird isn't great either). With that said, this deck can play through a majority of hand traps most of the time. It's even possible to play through Nibiru and, on rarer occassions, Maxx C if they don't draw Ash.

This is gonna be a really long bit of text (1180 words lmao), but here we go. Hopefully I can list at least most of what this deck can do, and how to actually use it. I won't go into how to beat it, but you can probably see how it works and reverse engineer it. 

Eventually I'll come back to edit this with some notes if anyone has any suggestions.

 

EXTREMELY IMPORTANT NOTE: When a card specifies a D/D card, that INCLUDES D/D/D cards. 

For your boss monster the main focus is to try and get D/D/D Flame High King Genghis on the field as soon as possible. Once you have him you just start making whatever extra deck monster with what you have. The alternative is getting D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex on the field, either by xyz climbing with D/D/D Marksman King Tell, and getting that from D/D/D Wave King Caesar. The other option is using literally any D/D/D on the field, then using contracts instead of xyz materials for Deviser's effect. 

To get D/D/D Flame High King Genghis, the general idea to do is have D/D Swirl Slime or Dark Contract with the Swamp King. If you don't have either you can use either Kepler or Contract with Gate to get them. 

D/D Savant Kepler ->Contract Gate OR Swamp King. Grab gate if you have swirl, swamp if you don't but have materials. 9 times out of 10 you want to have swirl in your hand though, but we'll get to that. 

 

Swirl Slime/Vice Typhon

Use Swirl as a way to get fusions on the field, or slot in a polymerization of some type. 

Swirl+Any lvl 4 or lower D/D -> Flame King or Oracle King. After that you should have more cards to work with and make other monsters. 

Swirl+Vice OR Necro Slime -> D/D/D Flame King with Vice, D/D Flame King with slime. Then afterwards you can use Vice or Necro's effect to summon another fusion. 

Vice+any D/D in Grave -> Since you'll have most likely D/D/D Flame out, I like to summon Oracle King for 2 reasons. 1, all dark contracts heal you instead. 2, its a level 8 fusion, so if you need to you could possibly bring out Duo Dawn King. BUT, only use this if you're completely done and have no other options, because of it's effect.

Necro+any D/D in grave -> Most of the time you'd have a Flame King out. Use these to get Oracle or one of the Fusions you can. 

 

Other Extra Deck Monsters

Now finally, the two big Fusions. D/D/D Wave Oblivion King Caesar Ragnarok is a really good going second/mid game use, but chances are you might not get there. D/D/D Super Doom King Purple Armageddon is a great board breaker with it's effect, and the burn is a nice bonus, along with the fact that you can use it every turn. 

D/D/D Abyss King Gilgamesh is a good way to bring some monsters on the field, even if they're from pendulum. Every pendelum effect is literally so good in most situations, so the only bad one to pick is maybe D/D Savant Thomas and D/D Gryphon. Every other one is situational, so get comfortable with their effects and when to use them. 

Now we're only running 1 synchro, being D/D/D Cursed King Siegfried. He's a really good spell negate for both your opponent's spells and on your own contracts if you don't want to take some damage. Combos include; Lamia+Vice and Orthos+Any lvl4 D/D. 

 

Other Cards

Now some specific card effects I didn't mention 

D/D Gryphon allows for much more flexibility for xyz and synchro summons with it's effect. 

D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok is good for longer games, and if you have other D/D/D's in your grave. 

Go! - D/D/D Divine Zero King Rage is really good for both it's pendelum effect as well as it's attacking directly effect. 

D/D Cerberus is good support for making R4 Wave King

D/D Lamia can be used to almost cycle itself to be used twice for summoning

D/D Ghost Does have a niche use, but since its not great all the time just side it. Can be used to wheel Swirl victims from banish.

D/D Savant Copernicus is useful in pendelum zone for dark contract damage negate to send it to grave (which can be used w/ vice and necro slime), and for summoning it to be a level 4 for xyz, while also being able to send necro slime or vice typhon to grave to use them for fusing. 

D/D Savant Galilei is good to bring contracts back to hand while sending it to the grave to help summon High Flame King from grave.  

Ash and Effect Veiler are just support for those weak points in the deck

 

Spell/Traps

Dark Contract with Patent License is good to have, but isn't necessary for the combot to function, and is all around a good support for the deck

One for One has a use with Lamia, but honestly could be swapped out if you want. A better alternative would be Called by the Grave 

D/D/D Headhunt is a good way to break your opponent's board, and some decks just fall apart if you take the right card. 

 

Final Notes/Suggestions

You could add in Baronne de Fleur if you wanted to and have that as a back up. It's just too good lmao

Dark Contract with the Witch is a good side addition if you want to have a way to both destroy other cards your opponent has, and stay a bit safer when it's not your turn with funny atk values.

D/D/D Gust High King Alexander is another funny card that you can build into to have the option to otk your opponents deck.

D/D/D Marksman King Tell's effect will not come up 90% of the time, but if you're in the late game you can use his effect to burn your opponent as a last resort. 

Most D/D/D monsters have this funny little effect that lets you bring back other D/D/D cards from grave. Take advantage of this to reuse summon fuel for fusions. 

 

Tl;dr- there is literally so much synergy here that is already here and that you can add onto it with other archetypes as well, especially fiends

 

I think that should be it! Leave a comment if I missed anything, or suggest something too. Anything counts, and lets try and make this have as much info as possible lmao. Ty if you made it this far, and if you didn't hopefully you'll find the actual deck as a good inspiration/reference tool.

deck_excerpt: One of the best trap decks out there, and allows complete freedom to outfit for any meta
deck_description: This deck tries to slow your opponent, especially Tearlments while building a board that is very difficult to break. All of the traps and ratios are to support the Dinomorphia fusion monsters while being able to search, draw or set traps from the deck. It's so much fun,and living on the edge by halving your LP is exhilerating. This is also this deck's greatest weakness, LP are always lower than your opponent, which is why Spooky Dogwood is in the side. The monster hand traps, besides Sauravis, should try to be used to summon Psychic End Punisher if possible, then using Alert to summon Rexterm back from GY for proper OTK.
Draw your deck
Use your chemical critters, or the chemicritters, to normal summon your way to victory by using gemini monsters!

The best way to play this is the same way as Invoked Shaddoll Dogmatika has been played historically, with a few differences. For one, you're going second. For two, I had to optimize it against Tearlaments, because they are an ever-present threat. 

The primary blind second power cards are Dark Ruler No More, Ultimate Slayer and Super Polymerization, though Shaddoll Fusion is also much more powerful going second rather than first. Your goal, essentially, is to break your opponent's board while building a nigh-unstoppable board yourself, as you trade your opponent's turn 1 setup with 1 or 2 tech cards from your hand, leaving your opponent with nothing to come back with. The deck is incredibly powerful for an oldy, but because of this particular spin on it I believe it may be able to hold out against Tearlaments.

Note that Dogmatika Maximus is being played in the main, and that depending on the matchup this can hinder more than help.

The side deck consists of: The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode for the big boards that can't be taken by Super Poly; Cosmic Cyclones and a Lightning Storm for backrow; Mask Change II for chain-blocking Aleister into Masked HERO Dark Law for the ultimate GY hate; Evenly Matched for the decks you know can't handle it; and Anti-Spell Fragrance & Solemn Judgment for turn 1 techs.

deck_excerpt: Witchcrafter is a consistent deck !! nanis
deck_description:
yo everyone welcome back, so till photon hyper nova drops, I'm going to post the top 6 decks we can build with photon Hydra nova cards.

LET'S START with the casual one, the Witchcrafters, the deck was really slow in the past, but thanks to undirect supports, this deck is faster than before, Vice-master is incredible. time to check what deck can do now!!
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Ways to fusion summon Vice-master:

3x Blazing Cartesia: quick effect you can fusion summon by using monsters in hand or field, this card with any other Witchcrafter can make vice-master.

3x Branded in high spirit: you can reveal 1 spellcaster from hand along with Grand-Guignol from the Extra deck, discard the spellcaster to add Cartesia from the deck, so this is by far a good starter.

3x fusion deployment: you can reveal Grand-Guignol and then special summon Cartesia from the deck so basically another starter, however, it's less good than branded in high spirit.

why do I play Grand-Guignol?

the first reason would be, I can reveal this card, by the effect of branded in high spirit, and send it to the GY, to add my combo starter, which is Cartesia

the second reason would be, I can special summon a dogmatika monster from my deck whenever an opponent tried to special summon a monster from the deck by a card effect in their turn or your turn, which you always summon Ecclesia or you can even summon Despian Proskenion from extra deck, which makes it hard for my opponent to deal with my board.

How do I make rank 4 XYZ plays here?

you can use vice-master to special summon Witchcrafterr schmietta ( the level 4 one ) and special summon Ecclesia from hand and make rank 4 xyz plays ( which rarely happens in first turn, but better than nothing )

* Ecclesia has 2 card effects, first one is you can special summon her if there is a monster special summoned from the extra deck ( this one does not lock you ) and the second effect is when this card is Ns or Ss you can add dogmatika card from the deck ( this effect locks you from extra deck summoning ) so just let you know.

why do we play spellbooks? 

spellbook of judgment is an insane card, not only can add any spellbooks from the deck, it also can special summon a spellcaster, and give you free spell discard for your Witchcrafter monsters effects. even if you activated 1 spell card you can summon Witchcrafter Genni and still do fine.

why do I play Artemis with Draco berserker?

Artemis helps you to link your Witchcrafter monsters, to be able to use their effects, and about Draco berserker, well Blazing Cartesia is a level 4 Tuner, so you can even make level 8 Synchro plays, but since Rank 4 XYZ plays were better to decide to play 1 synchro.

my side decks are different due to each format, this is the best side deck I came up with for the Witchcrafter deck.

Witchcrafter 7/10 good hands  -  6/10 OTK 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

thanks for reading, see you next time, with another of my Top 6 decks coming in Photon Hydra nova ( let me give you a tip < Stigmatika forever > )
CYA

deck_excerpt: I have no idea what this does
deck_description: Deck writeup in the Domain discord: https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

This is my version of Blackwing deck. It has some unique stuff and tons of standard stuff. The unique stuff I use here is Summon Breaker engine. 

Summon Breaker Is an interesting card that says "During Main Phase 1, if the turn player successfully conducts their third Summon of a monster(s) this turn: It becomes the End Phase." You can get rid of this on your turn easily by summoning Knightmare Unicorn and you maybe even won't need too. And yes, you can activate Metaverse in response to an effect that would summon a monster which would be third summon that turn to activate this card and end opponent's turn completly.

Anyways, let's explain how this deck works so that you can understand how to play this creation.

Blackwings are deck that can just spam the field, at least they were known for only that, but now they have much better combo potential with even 1.5 card combo with Blackwing - Simoon the Poison Wind that ends on 5 dissruptions. That is pretty good since Blackwings needed at least 3 cards to function and make maybe Apolloussa. Now they can do a lot of things alone. They can easily OTK and easily play a big control game with the mentioned combo and cards like Blackwing Full Armor Master that is just almost undestroyable.

1.5 card combo:

So, you need Blackwing - Simoon the Poison Wind and 1 other Blackwing monster in your hand. You will activate the effect of Simoon and banish the Blackwing in your hand to put Black Whirlwind in your S/T zone and Normal Summon Simoon as additional normal summon so that Whirlwind activates and enables you to search Blackwing - Sudri the Phantom Glimmer 

-Now you normal summon Sudri and use it's effect as chain link 1 and the effect of Whirlwing as chain link 2. With Whirlwind you will search Blackwing - Vata the Emblem of Wandering and with Sudri you will search Blackwing - Shamal the Sandstorm 

-Next we will activate the effect of Shamal to activate from the deck Black Feather Whirlwind and after that we will special summon Vata the Emblem 

-Use the effect of Vata on the field to send from the deck to the gy Blackwing - Harmattan the Dust and Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite to and Vata from field to synchro summon Black-Winged Dragon and then use the effect of Feather Whirlwind to revive Vata the Emblem

-You will now use Sudri and Vata the Emblem to synchro summon Blackwing - Nothung the Starlight and you will have Nothung beeing chain link 2 and Shamal as chain link 1. Nothung will inflict 800 damage to your opponent and Shaman will regive you Sudri from your gy by banishing itself

-Normal summon Sudri again and put Sudri as ch 1 and Black Whirlwind as ch 2. You are able to do this because Nothung gives additional normal summon. Whirlwind will search you Blackwing - Oroshi the Squall and with Sudri you will search Blackwing - Twin Shadow 

-Special summon Oroshi and use it and Black-Winged Dragon to synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss 

-Now you will activate the effect of Zephyros returning Black Whirlwind to your hand and summoning it to the field and when you do, you will use it and Sudri to xyz summon Evilswarm Nightmare (you cannot summon Bagooska with this because Bagooska isn't DARK monster, same with Dweller)

-And for the end use your Nothung and Simoon to xyz summon Wollow, Founder of the Drudge Dragons and set your Twin Shadow

Conclusion:

I think that for a deck that was at the bottom of rogue, this deck became really good and it can be played a lot ways. Phantom Knight's version is still possible but I think it is bad. With 2 cards (1.5 card combo) you have made 5 dissruptions. You could have 3 more dissruptios in hand on top of this or you can go maybe even further if you have "spam the field" cards like Blackwing - Bora the Spear . Anyways, have a nice day, I hope you like this deck.

deck_excerpt: COMBO GUIDE AT MY YOUTUBE: Seniorious
deck_description:
COMBO GUIDE AT MY YOUTUBE: Seniorious

The Decklist does not contain the TRUE staple/extra deck cards right now per request by my friend (Renren) who helped me made this combo guide.
just a christmas deck for my brother

Vampire Domain-Format Decklist

Domain Format Discord Link: https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

Any 1 vampire card in hand+empty board combo:

Normal Vampire Ghost
 -> Ghost effect, sending whatever for cost
 -> Send Retainer and add Shadow Vampire
 -> Retainer effect, sending Ghost on field
 -> Add Vampire Domination
 -> Effect of Ghost in GY to normal summon Shadow Vampire
 -> Shadow Vampire to special summon Voivode from deck
 -> Set Domination (Omni-Negate Counter Trap)

Other options:
 -> If Shadow Vampire is already in hand, add Fraulein for more damage/battle protection
 -> If Shadow Vampire is used as cost for Ghost, add Scarlet Scourge to recurr him instead
 -> If Domination is sent for Ghost cost, send Familiar instead of retainer for free Fraulein, or do combo as regular to add Vampire's Domain

This is a fun deck with some interesting combos letting you pull out synchros really easy. Your win con is relying on tenyi special summons to enable your red rose dragon to search for more black rose engine cards or letting your tenyi and sword soul cards carry you to synchro summons. Extra deck has a wide variety of tools. For instance Ruddy rose can empty your opponents graveyard and Chaos Ruler can fill it back up with tenyi cards. Pankratops is a multi use card with your level 3 and level 1 tuners. Protos and swordsoul engine can be searched with waterfall. You can easily adjust values too add more hand traps, but you should play all three engines (red rose, sword soul, and tenyi) to not brick as all three engines have synergy. You can summon mo ye for instance and then use basal to put out a red rose dragon your red rose can turn into a rose dragon and then summon a white rose dragon to the field to make a level 8 with the token tuner card left over for instance. It could be longyuan and red rose into denglong and another level 8 as well. I think there are alot of other synchro combos I haven't yet thought of, but just getting out the swordsoul synchro is already so strong. The advantage this deck has over swordsoul imo is that it lets you get to two level 10 tuners on turn 1 way more easily than traditional swordsoul. While you can still play swordsoul like normal that rose dragon cards at a bit of confusion since your opponent might not have expected a baron to come after a qixing and end up not playing a negate in their expecting a moye or taiya and not the red rose into baron that can't be negated without wasting two hand traps letting you get another rose dragon card to the field for even more synchro summons.

deck_excerpt: We've got em' all! Melffys, TriBrigades, Floowandeereze, Fur Hire, Springans, anything else you can thing of?
deck_description:
A Tri-Brigade Deck through and through! 
This deck's domain includes FIRE, TRI-BRIGADE, BEAST, WINGED-BEAST, and BEAST-WARRIOR due to the textbox reference of FRAKTALL the deckmaster. 
Do your normal Tri-Brigade stuff with absolutle certainty you'll start with Fraktall! Make Spright Elf and use it to revive the Melffy Wally in your GY! 
Take Advantage of Rugal, who can add a card from GY every turn, and captitalize on it by recurring Melffy Pinny! 
Take Advantage of the Multiplayer Format, to have "Folgo, Justice Fur Hire" draw 3 cards, 3 times, before its your turn again! 
Have "Shuraig, the Ominous Omen" be a menace and banish non-targetting every turn! (with help of Rugal/Spright Elf)

Melffy Engine in a Nutshell:

//Summon Wally ~> special Puppy + Catty from deck
//Melffy Catty adds any beast
//Melffy Puppy summons lv2 or lower beasts

//Adding Melffy Pinny let’s you (Quick Effect from Hand) send itself + Puppy or Catty -> Summon Merry Melffy
//Merry Melffy on summon: Target oppoment's monster, Bounce it

//Merry Melffy second effect returns itself to Extra Deck, tag-out into Melffy of Forest or Joyous Melffy 

Melffy engine sets up your graveyard
() Rugal -> target Melffy Pinny to add to hand
() Spright Elf (Quick Effect) can Revive Melffy PUPPY  or CATTY from GY, allowing you to search/summon every turn
USE CATTY or PUPPY over the course of 3 (of your opponent's) turns to access the rest of your deck
USE PINNY to continously summon "Merry Melffy", who keeps itself in the backpocket by returning to Extra Deck by its own effect!

(Melffy = branching access to the rest of the deck, use Tri-Brigade Airborne Assault, Melffy of the Forest, or Shuraig Search to tutor em out.)
Puppy: Kalantosa, Rodenut
Catty: Pinny, HopEar, Monkeyboard, Alpha

 

Fur Hires in a nutshell:

- Use Bearbrum to special summon Nervall
- Use Nervall to special summon Beast Warrior from Extra Deck
- Nerval (winged beast) + Bearbrum (beast) + Beast-Warrior (Scareclaw/Daruma Doll) = “Folgo, Justice Fur Hire” 
- Folgo Summon “Bravo, Fighter Fur Hire” from maindeck
- Use 2 remaining Winged-Beast-Warrior to make “Donner, Dagger Fur Hire” from Extra Deck

 With 3 names in field, you can now have Folgo draw 3 every turn (Bravo, Donner, Folgo)
(Given, that your opponent will destroy a card on the field)


Springans Cards in a nutshell:
Shared condition: [If a face up XYZ monster leaves the field by card effect…]
+ Our way of making XYZ “leave by card effect”: Joyous Melffy Target itself
+ How to get Joyous on field: Merry Melffy second effect, tag-out SS Melffy XYZ
+ Effects of Springan Cards: Prevent Attacks, Prevent Effect Activation, or Opponent Loses 1000atk. All continuous spells/traps that reactivate every turn (provided Joyous Melffy)

I know I've already made a Tearlaments deck but I do like coming up with weird ideas relating to them. This time, I'm using the metalfoes non-effect fusion monsters, who need for material a Metalfoes monster and any other monsters that have below a certain attack. Once those are on the field, you can use the Tenyi cards (which were milled by your Tearlaments) to build up board presence or break your opponent's field. This is just a random idea, so I likely won't actually get the cards for this one... Besides, I feel like this will be less consistent than the average Tearlaments deck (It doesn't help that I'm not willing to spend $200 on three reinohearts and three primeval planets).

Feedback is welcome if you have any, and I hope that this deck is either interesting, or gives you a good laugh.

deck_excerpt: TRAPTRIX Z-ARC || SOUL OF THE SUPREME KING || DIAMOND 1
deck_description:
1. Activate The Supreme King Souls,

2. Special summon Z-ARC,

3. Make sure there are 4 empty Monster Zones,

4. When your opponent activates the Spell Card, Activate The Supreme King Souls in GY, Special Summon 4 Dragon Monster (Pendulum Dragon, Xyz Dragon, Fusion Dragon, Synchro Dragon).

This is my Tri-Brigade Lyrilusc deck. One of my favourite decks and archtypes ever is Tri-Brigade. Something unique you will see here is Summon Breaker engine and main deck Tri-Brigade Oath . Summon Breaker engine is my favourite new avaible engine in the game as an interruption because it just stops your opponent's turn and Summon Breaker can still even if you have only access to it, be activated at the end of all of your plays getting your opponent some trouble with breaking your board. I am maining Oath because it can be a card I can maybe have access to in the gy through kitt if everything else is in my hand.

Anyways, I think you should, before picking up the deck, learn some combos so that you can start of something.

So for this following 1st combo you will need Fire Formation - Tenki , 1 Tri-Brigade monster that isn't Tri-Brigade Kerass 

-Activate Tenki and add to your hand from your deck Tri-Brigade Fraktall and use it's effect to send to the gy from deck Tri-Brigade Kitt which will then activate it's effect to send a Tri-Brigade card and you will send Tri-Brigade Nervall who will activate it's effect so that you can add Kerass.

-Normal summon Kerass and use it's effect banishing Kitt and Nervall from the gy to summon from extra deck Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom (it is important that the summoned Barren doesn't point into other monsters during it's existance unless they are link monsters)

-Now activate the effect of Barren to summon from your hand Fraktall and use Kerass and Ferrijit to link summon Tri-Brigade Bearbrumm the Rampant Rampager 

-Use Fraktall's effect and decide how much cards you will banish, you can banish 2 to summon Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords so that you can bounce opponent's cards or Hraesvelgr, the Desperate Doom Eagle to get rid of monsters in opponent's graveyard.

-For the end you are going to use Fraktall and Rampant to link summon into Tri-Brigade Rugal the Silver Sheller and use Rampant's effect to add Tri-Brigade Revolt and return another card to the bottom of the deck from your hand and then you will set that Revolt

Now you have access to 2 dissruptions and a free material with just 3 cards in a 2.5 card combo.

Now onto the second combo with the Lyrilusc cards. You will need Lyrilusc - Cobalt Sparrow and Lyrilusc - Bird Call and another card in hand

-You will activate Bird Call to add Lyrilusc - Sapphire Swallow and special summon your Cobalt Sparrow, then activate Cobalt's effect adding Tri-Brigade Nervall 

-Now you will use the effect of your Sapphire to summon from your hand both, Nervall and Sapphire (Nervall specificly in M-4)

-Use Cobalt and Sapphire to xyz summon Lyrilusc - Recital Starling and use it's effect to detach a material and add another Tri-Brigade Nervall

-Now normal summon Nervall you added and use it and another Nervall to xyz summon another Starling whose effect you will activate to add Lyrilusc - Turquoise Warbler and then Nervall's effect will activate allowing you to add Tri-Brigade Kerass 

-Use Kerass's effect to summon itself by discarding Warbler and activate Kerass's effect to banish 2 monsters from your gy and summon Tri-Brigade Bearbrumm the Rampant Rampager 

-Now to set up the board for the end you will use both Starlings to xyz summon into Number F0: Utopic Future and then you will use Utopic Future to xyz summon Number F0: Utopic Draco Future 

-You will now use kerass and rampant to link summon into Tri-Brigade Rugal the Silver Sheller and use the effect of Rampant to add Tri-Brigade Revolt and put another card to the bottom of the deck, then you set the Revolt.

As you can see with 2.5 card combo again you have multiple good dissruptions and since nervall will search card, like before in previous combo, you have a follow up plan if this board is cracked.

Conclusion:
Deck is really powerfull and really fun to play, this are just some of the combos, you can make them greater depending on your hand and I am sure you will win many games with this.

deck_excerpt: The only competitively viable build of Sky Striker with the banlist - fight alongside Raye and control your opponent to victory!
deck_description:
Raye and crew is part of the unfortunate club that suffers for the sins of the "Tear Zero" meta. All the anti-GY techs and new cards absolutely destroy any Sky Striker strategy since GY manipulation is the best way to counter Tearlaments. Bystial, Ishizu, all hard counter our favorite mech pilot Raye since they easily manipulate the GY, rendering her powerless and defenseless.

The Mystic Mine ban from the recent banlist proved to be the final nail in the coffin for competitive Sky Striker, losing their strong tool to slow down the meta which moves incredibly fast - way too fast for even Sky Striker cards to catch up.

HOWEVER, adversity forces dedicated Sky Striker players to let go of their crutches holding them back from truly skilled gameplay (I personally think Mystic Mine was a crutch :3) and it allows for some creativity to shine forth!

After a lot of brainstorming, Runick Sky Striker is the best idea I can come up with! Combining Sky Striker's control + resource generation with Runick's make for a extremely potent grindy deck! Since Sky Striker and Runick excel in a long grind game of resources, a combination of both of their strategies push each other to competitive viability! (I'm not coping I swear lmao)

Borrowing some ideas from earlier Runick Sky Striker lists established online, I made and tested my own list that best fits the current meta.

This deck is a variant of my earlier Runick strategy, "A Beginner's Guide to Naturia Runick," feel free to check it out for the full guide!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN


There are no straightforward combos with Runick Sky Striker. Your gameplan is hand dependent, and your win condition solely is out-resourcing your opponent with your Runick Fountain's +3 draw and Sky Striker's Engage and Multirole. If played properly and correctly, you should be able to control your opponent to death, and even deck them out.

Sky Striker's usual win condition of OTKing with Accesscode Talker or Linkage is usually unavailable with Runick, since the strategy skips your battle-phase, so your games generally tend to be a long-winded game of control and resources - one where Runick and Striker excels in.

The general set-up is establish Runick Fountain coupled with Multirole and Engage in rotation. With Runick Fountain, Multirole and Engage cycling every turn, you should be drawing 5 cards (3 with fountain and 2 with engage), recycling GY Sky Striker spells, and slowly but surely decking out your opponent until they surrender!

Start by summoning Hugin with any Runick quick-play spell. Get your +1-3 draw with Runick Fountain, then somehow summon the appropriate Sky Striker Ace in your Extra Monster Zone. If you have Linkage, you can use your Runick monster to summon a Sky Striker Ace (usually Kagari or Shizuku).

Set-up Multirole as well, since it effectively recycles your Sky Striker GY spells everyturn.

Although not ideal, you can also go for a purely milling strategy using Runick Allure. That card absolutely slaughters opponent's decks since Runick Sky Striker uses many quick play spells per turn. During testing, I found Allure to be a "win-more" card, and it didn't really contribute much to the gamestate/win condition of resources. The opponent would surrender knowing they will run out of resources much earlier than they would actually deck out due to Runick Allure. That's why I put Runick Allure and Munin in the side-deck.

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • If your opponent attempts to negate/remove Hugin with a targeting effect (ex. Imperm or Veiler), you can use Linkage to dodge the negate and summon a Sky Striker Ace.
  • Before recycling your Runick spells in your GY with Runick Fountain's draw effect, try to use your Sky Striker cards first since the GY is packed with spells - turning on your additional Sky Striker effects.
  • Sky Striker Eagle Booster works wonders for this deck - it allows you to dodge OTKs, renders your monster nigh invincible in the Extra Monster Zone for a turn, allows you to dodge negation - etc. Remember, it can be also used to protect your Runick monsters!
  • Remember that Runick Fountain can draw cards during your turn AND your opponent's turn! You can theoretically draw 6 cards before it's your turn again (given you have proper GY and hand set-up)! Remember to keep the GY and hand in mind when you use Runick spells.
  • Ishizu shufflers effectively shut down Runick Fountain's draw effect since it targets Runick spells in GY to shuffle back into your deck. Try to clear your opponent's GY shufflers with cards like Sky Striker Shark Cannon before attempting to activate Fountain's effect!
  • Runick spells skip only 1 Battle Phase - the Battle Phase is still an option for finishing off your opponent's life points. If your opponent has no more resources and you can attack for game, you can still enter the battle phase after you've skipped one earlier to finish off your opponent!
  • Decks that counter Tearlaments are usually also bad match-ups for this deck - like Floowandereeze and Dracoslayers (the variant that turbos out Necrovalley). Be sure to side appropriately for those match-ups. Luckily, this deck naturally outs anti-GY floodgates like Macro Cosmos, Necrovalley and Dimension Fissure with Runick and Sky Striker spells.

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

I WILL USE SKY STRIKER EVERY FORMAT!!! Even when Raye isn't competitively viable anymore, I WILL FIND A WAY TO PLAY SKY STRIKER!!! 

I know I'm coping hard (Lets face it, this deck is still a fragile "glass cannon"), but this deck is fairly terrifying when it gets going, using two quick play toolboxes to counter every threat my opponent comes up with. Need to negate a monster on the field? -> Widow Anchor and Freezing Curses! Need to destroy a card on the field? -> Afterburners and Flashing Fire! Need to protect your own card? -> Eagle Booster and Slumber!

I also find it thematically cool that instead of Sky Striker fighting for you, you're actually fighting ALONGSIDE Raye, since Runick implies you're the warrior on the field battling your opponent. So cool! Time to live out your favourite Elder Scrolls/DOOMSLAYER fantasy!

If you have any questions feel free to ask them below! Remember, Raye is Bae! (Even when the meta sucks for her)

deck_excerpt: A guidebook into how to play Dark Magician more properly.
deck_description:
This deck is probably the most consistent Dark Magician deck ever played. Reason is that it synergizes around the cards it plays and interact with. I will show you examples of why these choices are best. 

Your goal is to search both Rod for SoDM and Souls for DM (or DMG) to bring out The Dark Magicians. But this will show you other ways to draw and search other cards that can useful.

Rod can search: Circle, Bond, SoDM, Servant, Inheritance, DBM, and Eternal. 

Illusion can search: Rod, Timaeus, DM, DMG, Apprentice, and Souls. 

Servant can search: Rod, Illusion, DM, DMG, Apprentice, Souls, Circle, Bond, SoDM, Servant, Inheritance, DBM, Eternal, and even itself. 

Restage can summon: Souls (for a extender to bring out Crowley and a draw), Rod, and Spellbook Magician.

Crowley can search: Magician, Secrets, Knowledge, and Power (so you wont waste your normal summon, also you can add any Spellbook cards to your hand, super underrated underused card btw, def your key card also). 

Preparation can search Illusion and can be used for a draw (by Souls) and can be used for a banish (by Inheritance). Good synergy to have it at 3!

Magicalized can summon: Dragoon or Quintet (to backup Dragon Knight or Master of Chaos) to destroy monsters.

SoDM can OTK by attack or disrupt by summoning destruction: TDMs, Quintet, and Chimera (also who can draw cards).

Inheritance can banish Preparation, Restage, and etc Spell Cards you already used to search any DM Spell/Trap, including Servant and Eternal. 

You can still pull off the Bond combo to destroy the opponents field and you can setup the Dragon Knight lock combo also. 

This deck has a lot of combos and synergy. Very consistent opening hands as well. 

Tech choices: Piercing the Darkness = Spellbook of Power, Bond & DBM = Navigation & Combination, 2 Inheritance & 2 Prep = 1 Inheritance & 3 Prep and 2 Apprentice = 1 DMG. 

Another tech choice can be Branded Fusion (at 2), Albaz (at 1), Lubellion (at 1), Albion (at 1). The synergy would be to dump any DMs, DMGs, Palladiums for draw power while setting up the Dragon Knight lock. Also you can dump Souls in case if you have Restage in your hand to bring it back for a draw extender also. 

Best deck easily!

Enjoy the deck! More new Dark Magician support on the way!

deck_name: "D4RK DOMAIN" - Time Thief Regulator - Domain Format
deck_excerpt: Excuse me for one moment, my dog is ringing...
deck_description:
This is a Dark Rank 4 deck primarily based around the Time Thief/Raidraptor/Rokket Archetypes, with Time Thief Regulator as the deck master.

Regulator is an insane starter card that's basically a Rescue Cat but for level 4. The goal of the deck is to summon everyone's favourite annoying time travelling white haired anime boy and then roll from there, taking advantage of the fact that Redoer can peace out at practically any time to dodge removal. You have the potential for a fairly explosive turn 1 in which you'll end on Rusty with a set Fog Blade and Rank Up Magic Force, and Dark Rebellion Xyz Dragon ready to rank up into Dark Requiem Xyz Dragon; while also having the ability to play a slower midrange game thanks to Redoer and the fact that Rokket monsters all float when destroyed.

 

Domain is a 60 card singleton format in which your deck must be themed around a single monster card, the "Deck Master". Join the Domain Format discord server and take a look at the rules if you're interested: https://discord.gg/GxXHC4qCYM

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes White Dragon Personal Build - need assistance minimizing deck
deck_description: A nostalgia driven build from someone returning to Yu-Gi-Oh. Made from 2 Saga of the Blue-Eyes White Dragon Structure Decks (2022) and 1 Dark Legion Starter Deck (2015). Goal is to support and create opportunities for Blue-Eyes White Dragon & D/D/D Dragon King Pendragon. Need assistance from experienced deck builders on how to efficiently minimize this deck so feel free to leave suggestions.
HAVE FUN

Yubel as an archetype is very interest to build around. The main pros of Yubel is that she is cool to play and it will make your opponent concede. The main combo is to get Yubel summoned, activated chain destruction on yourself, destroy yubels in your hand or field to summon 2 Yubel Terror Incarnates while still having the original Yubel on the field. End phase, priority says you can make 1 Terror Incarnate kill the other and base Yubel, making it so you have the Ultimate Nightmare on your field with another Terror Incarnate on the board. Prevent your opponent from killing your Yubel forms with 'Mound of the Bound Creator' and make them angry by playing 'Savage Colliseum'. Only one field spell allowed so go for whatever makes your combos good. Deck centered around forcing your opponent to hit your Yubels, and cycling through them with Traps that bring Yubels back to the field to start the combos over again. 

Trap Trick is to search for Chain Destruction or any trap that is useful to your current hand.

If Yubel is in your hand, try and summon it with 'Stygian Patrol', or tribute summon it with 'Fires of Doomsday'. 

If you have Mystic Tomato, you let it die and let it summon Yubel, with Sangan, search a Yubel or Mystic Tomato.

If you don't have any Yubels, either search it with the search monsters, or summon it from the graveyard with alot of traps and effects in this deck.

Side deck cards are excellent to play to immediately get Yubel on the field, as 'Neos Kluger' has Yubel listed as a material, so you play the spell and get base Yubel on the field. I don't have it in my irl deck because I can't find it anywhere!

 

Have fun with Yubel because it's an incredibly fun deck to play! Show some Yubel some love

deck_excerpt: For the ppl that wanna win their locals
deck_description:
Don't have the money to invest in the "Tear 0" format? Tired of losing at your local OTS? Or are you just tired of your friends comboing off in front of you? Have you considered... cancer??? Well, I've got the deck for you! Introducing:

"I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. I swear this is a very skill-based deck. GAAAAAAAAAAAA-" Budget Floo.

Floo is the "budget" option in this current "Tear 0" format and for good reason. It's one of the easiest control decks to pick up since all you'll be doing is normal summoning a bunch of birds and locking your opponent from special summoning anything using Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds. The main deck at the lowest rarity and using alternatives is worth around $40-50. This is in comparison to Tearlament where you basically have to pull a Left Arm Offering to even get it.

When building a Floowandereeze deck, you have options to make the deck vary from other builds, like in DistantCoder's build where he plays the Dogmatika engine. If you have leftover money, you can replace Jack in the Hand with Advent. You generally don't have to care much about building your extra deck since most of the time you're not special summoning at all and it's really only used by Pot of Prosperity or in this case, Pot of Extravagance.

The side deck in this build could literally be anything. If you don't have any of the cards in the extra deck that every other deck is playing (i.e. Kitkallos, Toadally Awesome, etc.) you can replace Ghost Reaper with Infinite Impermanence or Dark Ruler No More.

That's pretty much about it really, have fun. :)

the difference between IDO, TCG AND OCG  ruling: 

In the TCG, "Ido the Supreme Magical Force" does not prevent Sets, so you can Tribute it for a Tribute Set.

 

In the OCG, "Ido the Supreme Magical Force" prevents Sets, so you cannot Tribute it for a Tribute Set.

Few decks are as fun to play in YuGiOh as Amazoness. And boy, are they fun in speed duels. Let's break it down.

First, let’s start with the monsters. We'll be running (3) Swords Woman, (2) Amazoness Trainee, (2) Amazoness Spy, (1) Amazoness Sage, and (1) Chain Master. Swords Woman is far and away our best monster, and quite possibly the best card in the deck. Paired with Heirloom, this card can use it's effect to lay some fat damage on the opponent. Trainee is a great way to keep your opponent’s monsters out of their graveyard, and if successful can increase its attack with each kill. Spy is there for a free special summon, Sage is extra back row hate, and Chain Master is a great 1-up to snatch one of your opponent’s monsters. With a steep cost of 1500 Life Points to use, we don't need to run more than one.

For spells, we are running (1) Village, (2) Amazoness Heirloom, (2) Hammer Shot, and (2) Night Beam. Village is a staple to run in the deck as it not only boosts our attack, but also gives us a free special summon when an Amazon is destroyed. Heirloom is our key pair card for Swords Woman as it not only protects us from an attack, but also allows an Amazon to beat over a bigger monster and destroy it for free. Hammer Shot is a must include as many meta decks run Jinzo and that's usually the highest attacking monster on the field. Finally, Night Beam is great backrow removal that your opponent’s cannot chain the targeted card to, which is very helpful.

Lastly, we are running just a small handful of traps: (2) Amazoness Archers, and (2) Kunai with Chain. Archers is a classic way to get your opponent’s 4-star beaters to attack into you and lose some life points, and Kunai is an essential card for protection and (more) attack boost. It’s more important feature, however, is being able to switch an enemy's monster to defense position.

The side deck is a mixed bag of cards that will be helpful in many situations. Sinister Serpant will pair very well with Tribute, so give it a try. Anyways, that's all for today, so have fun!
